author: @morthim
text: if i get a model running on my own hardware (which is far worse). i'll take up your offer. especially since it is also sorta a chat bot. do you have voice recognition done? if not, to really use it effectively that would need to be a first step. the training method i'm considering is taking youtube videos with subtitles, and training it on those. beautiful soup should be able to get subtitles, and the file size would be smaller if you just temporarily download the videos into ram, scan them, and then only save the results. you would have only a list of files. and since there are unscrupulous things that can hide in videos, one can choose good ones at random.   the two or three premptive layers are to take the videos, parse the sound for transcribed sounds, and then convert the sounds through some sort of transformation into words. it will allow english crap like "though through those ..." to be spelled correctly.   it will be slow, but the huge amount of possible testing and trainign data, means that if you cache a few videos of different types it will be hard to over train the data. 30 videos all kept in ram, and then configuring so that the net trains untill their output matches train data 80% of the time, will allow lots of cycles through the local video data. then you cycle in new data. it is time expensive but if you don't already have one, it gets you a basic transcriber.
